SIMPLE: noddy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Noddy
<hw>Nod"dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Noddies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Prob. fr. <ets>nod</ets> to
incline the head, either as in assent, or from drowsiness.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A simpleton; a fool.</def>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> tomnoddy.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any tern of the
genus <gen>Anous</gen>, as <spn>Anous stolidus</spn>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The arctic fulmar (<spn>Fulmarus glacialis</spn>). Sometimes also
applied to other sea birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An old game at cards.</def>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small two-wheeled one-horse vehicle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An inverted pendulum consisting of a short vertical
flat spring which supports a rod having a bob at the top; -- used for
detecting and measuring slight horizontal vibrations of a body to which
it is attached.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Node</ent>⟦br⟧
